                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d387">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.00/7–2144: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in China</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Gauss</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Chungking</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1944-07-21T14:00:00+07:00"
                            >July 21, 1944—2 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received July 21—1:30 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>1257. Wang Shih-chieh told the Counselor last evening that no progress is being
                    made in negotiations with the Communists. (Paragraph 3 our 1158, July 4<note
                        n="8" xml:id="d387fn8">
                        <hi rend="italic">Ante</hi>, <ref target="#pg_113">p. 113</ref>.</note>.)
                    Latter’s representative here stating that anticipated instructions from Yenan
                    have not been received. Wang expressed opinion that Communist leaders were
                    waiting outcome of Hunan fighting before making reply to Generalissimo’s
                    “counter proposals”.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Gauss</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
